Exercise 5.3.4 - Ridge and Lasso Cross-Validation

W. Mangrobang

August 29, 2018

Breast Cancer Data Set

1. Implement the provided trial-and-error CV process with the breast cancer data as split previously to set lambda values for ridge and lasso regression.
  • Note that the function cv.glmnet() will do cross validation over the lambda values for you, although not over the alpha values. You can choose to use this function or implement cross validation yourself.
  1. Split the data into training and test sets (80%/20% or otherwise):
# load data
bc.all <- read.csv("/users/werlindo/dropbox/pacp/data/BreastCancerWisconsinDataSet.csv")

# create binarized target
bc.all$target[bc.all$diagnosis == "M"] = 1
bc.all$target[bc.all$diagnosis == "B"] = 0
bc.all$target <- as.factor(bc.all$target)  # This is to force the logistic regression to predict 0/1

# select variables available for training
bc.all <- bc.all[, setdiff(colnames(bc.all), c("diagnosis", "id", "X"))]

# split data into training vs testing; 80%/20%
set.seed(2425)

library(caret)  # get createDataPartition
train <- createDataPartition(bc.all$target, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)

# allocate datasets
bc.train <- bc.all[train, ]
bc.test <- bc.all[-train, ]

The following steps we will use cv.glmnet

  1. Split the training data into n folds (for n-fold cross validation).

  2. Select a list of values you want to test, e.g.:
  • lambda = (0.01, 0.1, 0.5, 1)
  • alpha = (0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1)

Note that if only performing ridge or lasso regression, you only need to worry about lambda.

  1. For each pair of values (or single value for lasso or ridge):
    A. Train the model on (n-1) folds of the training data using those values.
    B. Calculate the prediction error on the remaining fold of training data.
    C. Repeat n times for each fold in the training data (cross validation).
    D. Calculate the average error rate across all iterations in the cross validation (cross validation error).

  2. Take the pair of values that gives the lowest cross validation error.

  3. Train a model on all of the training data using the optimal hyperparameters.

  4. Test the model on the test data.

Ridge Regression Cross-Validation

We will use cv.glmnet to run the cross-validations.

For \(\lambda\)’s, we’ll use: (0.01, 0.1, 0.5, 1, 10).

library(glmnet) #regressions

# Set up the formula (model form)
# Know that target is last of 31 columns, so take 1:30
formula.lm <- as.formula(paste("target~",paste(colnames(bc.train[,c(1:30)]),collapse = "+")))
 
# Here is a clever way to create the data matrix. This one doesn't require keeping track of which columns contain the features.
X <- model.matrix(formula.lm, data = bc.train)

# Set up lamdbas
lambdas <- c(0.01, 0.1, 0.5, 1, 10)
?cv.glmnet

# Cross Validation
cvfit.r = cv.glmnet(X
                  , y = bc.train$target
                  , family = "binomial"
                  , type.measure = "class"
                  , alpha = 0 #Ridge
                  , lambda = lambdas
                  )
plot(cvfit.r)

Default number of folds, per the documentation, is 10.

To get the \(\lambda\) that gives minimum mean cross-validated error we can use cvfit.r$lambda.min; this \(\lambda\) turns out to be 0.01.

Lasso Regression Cross-Validation

Assuming same \(\lambda\)’s: (0.01, 0.1, 0.5, 1, 10).

cvfit.l = cv.glmnet(X
                  , y = bc.train$target
                  , family = "binomial"
                  , type.measure = "class"
                  , alpha = 1 #Lasso
                  , lambda = lambdas
                  )
plot(cvfit.l)

To get the \(\lambda\) that gives minimum mean cross-validated error we can use cvfit.l$lambda.min; this \(\lambda\) turns out to be 0.01 as well.

2. Test both models on the test data and calculate the prediction error. Compare the results of the two models (including the coefficients). What do you notice?
# Get matrix input for test data
X.test <- model.matrix(formula.lm, data = bc.test)

# Get predictions from both cv sets for 'optimal' lambdas
res.ridge <- as.data.frame( as.double( predict(cvfit.r, newx = X.test, s = "lambda.min", type = "class") ) )
colnames(res.ridge) <- c('res.ridge')
res.lasso <- as.data.frame( as.double( predict(cvfit.l, newx = X.test, s = "lambda.min", type = "class") ) )
colnames(res.lasso) <- c('res.lasso')

# Bind it to the the testing set
bc.test <- cbind( bc.test, res.ridge, res.lasso )

#We'll use a custom function for accuracy. 
accuracy = function(truth, pred) {
  # confusion matrix
  cmat = table(truth, pred)
  sum(diag(cmat))/sum(cmat)
}

#create empty dataframe to store accuracy results
acc <- data.frame( model=as.character(), accuracy=as.double())

#Calc accuracy
acc <- rbind(acc, data.frame( model='Ridge', accuracy=accuracy(bc.test$target, bc.test$res.ridge)))
acc <- rbind(acc, data.frame( model='Lasso', accuracy=accuracy(bc.test$target, bc.test$res.lasso)))

#Make a table
library(kableExtra) #kable

# Let's make a pretty table
acc.tbl <- acc %>%
  kable() %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "striped", font_size = 10, full_width = FALSE, position = "left") %>%
  row_spec(1, bold = T, color = "white", background = "orange")
acc.tbl
model accuracy
Ridge 0.9734513
Lasso 0.9557522

Both models had lambda.min of 0.01, which makes for pretty straighforward comparison. Given that we see that the ridge regression is just a little more accurate on the test set; 0.9734513 vs 0.9557522 for lasso.

As we’ve seen before, as we alpha increases, more variables/features get pushed to zero (implicit variable selection); the potential downside is that less information could lead to less accuracy.

The following is a heatmap of the coefficients for the ridge and lasso regressions, for comparison.

# Get the cv fits
fit.ridge <- cvfit.r$glmnet.fit
fit.lasso <- cvfit.l$glmnet.fit

# Get just the betas (coefficients)
betas.ridge <- as.matrix(fit.ridge$beta)
betas.lasso <- as.matrix(fit.lasso$beta)

# Get just the coefficients where lambda is lambda.min
betas.ridge <- betas.ridge[,which(fit.ridge$lambda==cvfit.r$lambda.min)]
betas.lasso <- betas.lasso[,which(fit.lasso$lambda==cvfit.l$lambda.min)]

df.betas <- as.data.frame(cbind(betas.ridge,betas.lasso))

library(tidyverse) #rownames_to_column
df.betas <- rownames_to_column(df.betas)
colnames(df.betas)[1] <- 'features'

#Melt it
df.betas.melted <- gather( df.betas, key = model, value = coefficients, -features)

#Plot heatmap
p <- ggplot(df.betas.melted, aes(x=model, y=features)) + geom_tile(aes(fill = coefficients),
     colour = "white") + scale_fill_gradient2(low = "steelblue",
     high = "green", mid = "white") +
     theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 0, hjust = 0)) 
    # geom_text(aes(label=coefficients))
p

Note that there is far more white for the lasso results, i.e. more of the coefficients got pushed to 0.

3. Also compare the results to running ordinary least squares regression on the training data and calculating prediction error on the test data. What do you notice?
# Recreate numeric versions of target variable
bc.train$target.num[bc.train$target == "1"] <- 1
bc.train$target.num[bc.train$target == "0"] <- 0

bc.test$target.num[bc.test$target == "1"] <- 1
bc.test$target.num[bc.test$target == "0"] <- 0

# Rewrite formula with numeric target
formula.ols <- as.formula(paste("target.num~",paste(colnames(bc.train[,c(1:30)]),collapse = "+")))

# Run OLS

OLS is not appropriate for predicting on binary variables. Looking at the results we see values that are ’kind of around" 0 and 1, but without some sort of rubric, we can’t really translate this to final predictions, e.g. which should be considered 0’s and 1’s. Logistic regression is more approriate.

If we revisit the non-regularized logistic regressions we’ve performed prior, we see that the accuracy rate is around 96%, in the neighborhood of our above results.
